{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525508"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:15:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:15:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14079"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14079"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.33,0.24,0.02,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53643"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6745"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14079"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39104"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1554"},{"type":"tags","id":"1892"},{"type":"tags","id":"2943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6362"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12906"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43477"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53643"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old Indigenous woman presents to the Emergency Department with painful skin lesions that have developed over the past two weeks. She has a medical history of end-stage kidney disease on haemodialysis for the past seven years, type 2 diabetes mellitus, bronchiectasis, and a mechanical mitral valve (secondary to rheumatic heart disease). Her medications include linagliptin, gliclazide, insulin, salbutamol, sevelamer, calcitriol, erythropoietin, metoprolol and warfarin. She works as a librarian and has not travelled recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 142/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There are several tender, violaceous, reticular lesions on her thighs and abdomen. Some of the lesions have central areas of necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum calcium: 2.6 mmol/L (2.2-2.7)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum phosphate: 2.4 mmol/L (0.8-1.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParathyroid hormone: 68 pmol/L (1.6-6.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR: 2.8\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant risk factor for this patient\u0027s skin condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatic heart disease","Warfarin use","Diabetes mellitus","Bronchiectasis","Erythropoietin use"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of calciphylaxis, also known as calcific uremic arteriolopathy. The painful, violaceous, reticular lesions with areas of necrosis are characteristic of this condition. Calciphylaxis is a rare but serious disorder that occurs primarily in patients with end-stage kidney disease (ESKD) and is associated with high morbidity and mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin use\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant risk factor for calciphylaxis in this patient. Warfarin inhibits vitamin K-dependent proteins that normally prevent vascular calcification. In patients with ESKD, who are already at risk for calciphylaxis due to abnormal calcium and phosphate metabolism, warfarin use significantly increases this risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is a risk factor for calciphylaxis, but it is not as significant as warfarin use. Diabetes can contribute to vascular calcification and endothelial dysfunction, which may increase susceptibility to calciphylaxis, but the association is not as strong as warfarin use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatic heart disease\u003C/strong\u003E itself is not a direct risk factor for calciphylaxis. While it has led to the need for a mechanical valve and subsequent warfarin use in this patient, it is the warfarin that increases the risk, not the underlying cardiac condition. Acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease are conditions which have a higher prevalence in the Indigenous population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchiectasis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a known risk factor for calciphylaxis. While it is a chronic condition that can impact overall health, it does not directly contribute to the pathophysiology of calciphylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythropoietin use\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with an increased risk of calciphylaxis. Erythropoietin is used in many patients with end-stage kidney disease to treat anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of calciphylaxis includes consideration of warfarin cessation (a challenging situation in this patient given the patient\u0027s important indication for anticoagulation - mechanical heart valve), intensifying dialysis, correcting calcium and phosphate imbalances, and considering treatments such as sodium thiosulfate. Early recognition and management are crucial due to the high mortality rate associated with this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn caring for Indigenous patients, it is important to consider cultural factors that may influence medical care. An appreciation of connection to country, involvement of Aboriginal Liaison Officers and interpreters where appropriate, and a holistic approach to care are crucial.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calciphylaxis presents with painful, violaceous skin lesions that can progress to necrotic ulcers.","Warfarin is a significant risk factor for calciphylaxis in patients with end-stage kidney disease.","Calciphylaxis has a high mortality rate, emphasising the importance of early recognition and management."],"references":["Calciphylaxis: Causes, Symptoms, and Management. In: DermNet [Online]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/calciphylaxis","Gallo Marin B, Aghagoli G, Hu SL, Massoud CM, Robinson-Bostom L. Calciphylaxis and Kidney Disease: A Review. American Journal of Kidney Diseases. 2023;81(2):232-9. Available at: https://www.ajkd.org/article/S0272-6386(22)00849-6/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39104"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14079"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39104"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T16:23:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T16:28:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6745"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53643"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"